Q18: If the patient signed a release saying they wanted their MD or trusted relative/advisor to know about a med refusal - that's fine.  Otherwise, no.  I presume competency even with a major mental illness.
This is a tough one. He is not a child, but the medicine is important. Also, how is the robot going to know if he actually took it or just threw it out?

Many patients today have detailed medical directives set up ahead of time. If I was a care giver, I'd want to know if said directives were in place and how much leeway I had in my decision making abilities.
Thanks good luck with your work
I hope in the near future robots can make the company to elderly people and also take care of them.
